{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638352"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17705"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72025"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10419"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57495"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10436"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24338"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72025"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe optic chiasm is an important anatomical structure in the visual pathway where nerve fibres from each retina meet and partially decussate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pattern of nerve fibre crossing at the optic chiasm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporal retinal fibres cross while nasal fibres remain uncrossed","No fibres cross at the chiasm","All fibres from both retinas cross","Nasal retinal fibres cross while temporal fibres remain uncrossed","Superior retinal fibres cross while inferior fibres remain uncrossed"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt the optic chiasm, \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal retinal fibres cross while temporal fibres remain uncrossed\u003C/strong\u003E. This partial decussation ensures that visual information from the left visual field is processed by the right occipital cortex, and vice versa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal retinal fibres cross while nasal fibres remain uncrossed\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement would result in incorrect processing of visual fields, as each hemisphere would receive information from the wrong side of vision.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo fibres cross at the chiasm\u003C/strong\u003E - Without any crossing of fibres, each hemisphere would only receive information from the ipsilateral eye, preventing proper integration of visual information.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll fibres from both retinas cross\u003C/strong\u003E - Complete crossing would result in each visual cortex receiving information from the wrong visual field.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior retinal fibres cross while inferior fibres remain uncrossed\u003C/strong\u003E - The separation of crossing fibres occurs along the vertical meridian (nasal/temporal), not the horizontal meridian (superior/inferior).\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis arrangement allows for binocular vision and depth perception, as each hemisphere receives information from both eyes about the contralateral visual field.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The optic chiasm is where approximately 50% of retinal nerve fibres cross to the opposite side of the brain.","Nasal retinal fibres cross at the optic chiasm while temporal fibres remain uncrossed.","This anatomical arrangement ensures each visual cortex processes information from the contralateral visual field."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57495"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57495"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:14:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:15:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10419"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72025"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":nul